name: edible portion
comments: The ‘edible portion’ is defined as (100 – refuse), where refuse is the inedible weight as a percent taken away from the “as purchased” or “as acquired” food before analysing the 100g edible part. If another definition is used, it should be specified.

name: refuse
comments: Synonyms: or inedible material (also called waste)The refuse is defined as (100 – edible portion),  and represents the inedible weight as a percent of the “as purchased” or “as acquired” food before analysing the 100g edible part. If another definition is used, it should be specified. In addition to providing a value, it may be necessary to describe refuse in a food descriptor field.

name: Rubner conversion factors using available carbohydrate kilocalories
comments: Rubner conversion factors using available carbohydrate kilocalories = (4.1 x g total protein) + (3.75 x g available carbohydrate expressed as monosaccharides) + (9.3 x g total           fat) + (7 x g alcohol).

name: Rubner conversion factors using total carbohydrate           kilocalories
comments: Rubner conversion factors using total carbohydrate           kilocalories = (4.1 x g total protein) + (4.1 x g total carbohydrate) + (9.3 x g total fat) + (7 x g alcohol).

name: Sum of arginine + histidine
comments: Sum of arginine and histidine (from Slovak).

name: amino acids, total non-essential
comments: Sum of 11 non-essential amino acids: alanine, asparagine, aspartic acid, cysteine, glutamic acid, glycine, hydroxyproline and hydroxylysine, proline, serine, tyrosine (from Slovak)

name: hydroxylysine
comments: 5-hydroxylysine, non-essential amino acid. Hydroxylysine is found only in animal proteins and mostly in collagens (from Slovak table).

name: Taurine
comments: Non-protein amino acid with sulfonic acid group (NCI).

name: connective tissue protein
comments: This term is not precisely defined in the table in which it appears. The Tagname should be construed as ``connective tissue protein as the term is used by Souci-Fachmann-Kraut''

name: chromoproteins
comments: class of conjugated proteins, such as hemoglobin, that contains a pigmented prosthetic group, such as heme. From Slovak table

name: Sphingolipid
comments: A class of dietary lipids containing a long-chained sphingosine group (unsaturated amino alcohol with formula C18H37NO2), fatty acids bound to the NH2 group as an amide, and either sugars or phosphoric acid and alcohols bound to the primary hydroxy group (NCI)

name: Fatty Acid 16:2
comments: Hexadecadienoic Acid. A polyunsaturated fatty acids with 16 carbons and 2 double bonds.

name: Fatty Acid 16:3
comments: Hexadecatrienoic Acid. A polyunsaturated fatty acids with 16 carbons and 3 double bonds.

name: fatty acids, total n-3
comments: A class of fatty acids with the first double bond at the 3rd carbon from the methyl end.

name: fatty acids, total n-6
comments: A class of fatty acids with the first double bond at the 6th carbon from the methyl end.

name: Phosphatidic Acid
comments: Simplest form of dietary phospholipid consisting of glycerol bound to two fatty acids and a phosphate group. (NCI)

name: Plasmalogen
comments: A glycerophospholipid with an enol ether double bond in the sn-1 position of its glycerol backbone. (NCI)

name: carbohydrate, available; calculated by difference
comments: This value is calculated: 100 g minus total grams of water, protein, fat, alcohol, ash and dietary fibre; or CHOCDF – dietary fibre.

name: carbohydrate, available;  method unknown or variable
comments: This tag should be used if method is unknown or undocumented; may also be used if combinations of methods are used to calculate a mean.

name: Mannose
comments: A hexose which is an epimer at C-2 of glucose.  Structurally, it is a glucose with the OH and H groups interchanged at carbon-2. (NCI)

name: Fucose
comments: A hexose whose structure can be derived from galactose replacing the -OH group on carbon 6 with a hydrogen. (NCI)

name: polysaccharides, total
comments: Sum of starch and non-starch-polysaccharides. DP >10

name: starch, resistant RS1
comments: Resistant starch (RS1): physically protected or encapsulated, as in whole and partly milled grains.

name: starch, resistant RS2
comments: Resistant starch (RS2): raw starchy foods, such as potatoes and green banana.

name: starch, resistant RS3
comments: Resistant starch (RS3): retrograded starch that has been gelatinised and then cooled.

name: starch, resistant RS4
comments: Resistant starch (RS4): starch in which chemical modification confers amylase resistance.

name: starch, particially hydrolysed; expressed in monosaccharide equivalents
starch, modified; expressed in monosaccharide equivalents
maltodextrin
comments: Partially hydrolysed starch. Classification? ALSO IN MONOSACCH. EQ?

name: Galactan
comments: Galactan is a polymer of the sugar galactose. It is found in hemicellulose and can be converted to galactose by hydrolysis.

name: galacturonic acid
comments: D-Galacturonic acid is a sugar acid, the oxidized form of D-galactose. It is the main component of pectin, in which it exists as the polymer polygalacturonic acid

name: erythritol
comments: from Slovak table. Erythritol (butane-1,2,3,4-tetraol) is a natural sugar alcohol

name: formic acid
synonyms: methanoic acid, hydrogen carboxylic acid, aminic acid

name: glycolic acid
comments: Glycolic acid (or hydroxyacetic acid) is the smallest α-hydroxy acid (AHA).

name: bismuth
comments: non essential trace element. (From Slovak table)

name: molybdenum 4+
comments: Molybdenum ion requiring four electrons to return to its elemental state.

name: nickel 2+
comments: Nickel ion requiring two electrons to return to its elemental state.

name: titanum
comments: Non essential trace element. (From Slovak table)

name: cesium
comments: Non essential trace element. (From Slovak table) includes cesium (isotope 133)

name: Summation, all-trans retinol equivalents = all-trans retinol + 0.75 13-cis retinol + 0.90 retinaldehyde
comments: Used in the McCance and Widdowson (British) table

name: Conversion factor for retinol equivalent of retinaldehyde
Conversion factor for retinol equivalent of 13-cis retinol
carotenoids, total
comments: cis and trans carotenoids, including non provitamin a carotenoids. This class includes carotenes, xanthophylls and may also include certain compounds that arise from rearrangement of the skeleton of ψ,ψ-carotene or by loss of part of this structure. Retinoids are excluded.

folate, sum of vitamers, determined by HPLC
comments: Sum of folate vitamers determined by HPLC. Includes mostly tetrahydrofolate, 5-methyltetrahydrofolate, 5-formyltetrahydrofolate, 10-formylfolic acid, 10-formyldihydrofolate and folic acid

name: folate, conjugated
comments: Sum of polyglutamic forms of folates.

name: Conversion factor for dietary folate equivalent of synthetic folic acid
tetrahydrofolate
comments: Natural tetrahydrofolates occur only in the (6S)-form

phytosterol, unsaturated
comments: Phytosterol with at least one double bond in the sterol ring.
